Note: ========================================
Note: ARM Assembly Parser
Note: ========================================
Note: Parser for ARM assembly language (ARMv7/ARMv8)
Note: Part of the Translation translation system
Note: Builds AST from token stream
Note: ========================================

Import "compiler/middle/gungnir/hir/translation/frontends/arm/arm_lexer.runa" as Lexer
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/collections/list.runa" as List
Import "compiler/frontend/primitives/memory/layout.runa" as Layout

Constant ARM_INSTRUCTION as Integer is 1
Constant ARM_DIRECTIVE as Integer is 2
Constant ARM_LABEL as Integer is 3
Constant ARM_REGISTER as Integer is 4
Constant ARM_IMMEDIATE as Integer is 5
Constant ARM_MEMORY as Integer is 6
Constant ARM_REGISTER_LIST as Integer is 7
Constant ARM_SHIFTED as Integer is 8
Constant ARM_IDENTIFIER as Integer is 9

@Reasoning:
A uniform AST node shape lets the rest of the pipeline (arm_to_hir, validators)
walk the tree by inspecting node_type and recursing through a single children
list, regardless of whether the node represents an instruction, directive,
register, immediate, or label. Lexeme info is carried inline so to_hir can
recover the original bytes without revisiting the source.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
node_type holds an ARM_* constant at offset 0, value is a pointer into the
source bytes at offset 8, value_length is the lexeme length at offset 16,
children is a List of child ArmNode handles at offset 24. Total record size
is 32 bytes.
@End Implementation

Type called "ArmNode":
    node_type as Integer
    value as Integer
    value_length as Integer
    children as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Carries the in-progress parse state: the producing lexer, the token list
pulled from that lexer, and the current cursor index. Keeping the token list
pointer locally avoids re-reading it from the lexer on every advance.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
lexer at offset 0 retains the source/token owner, tokens at offset 8 is the
cached List pointer, current at offset 16 is the integer index of the next
unconsumed token. Total record size is 24 bytes.
@End Implementation

Type called "ArmParser":
    lexer as Integer
    tokens as Integer
    current as Integer
End Type

@Reasoning:
Constructor that snapshots the lexer's token list at construction time;
parse must be called after the lexer has finished tokenize, otherwise the
parser will see an empty list.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 24 bytes, writes the lexer pointer at offset 0, reads the lexer's
tokens List pointer from lexer offset 24 and stores it at parser offset 8,
initialises current to 0 at offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_parser" takes lexer as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new parser from lexer

    Let parser be proc allocate from Layout with 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 0, lexer
    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with lexer, 24
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 8, tokens
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, 0
    Return parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
The parser does not own the lexer or the token list (the lexer does), so it
only needs to release its own 24-byte record. The AST it produced lives
independently and must be freed via destroy_arm_node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Single Layout.deallocate on the parser record.
@End Implementation

Process called "destroy_parser" takes parser as Integer:
    Note: Free parser

    proc deallocate from Layout with parser
End Process

@Reasoning:
ArmNodes own their children list and (transitively) their children. Recursive
post-order destruction is the only safe pattern; freeing parent first would
leak descendants because we hand back ownership of children via add_child.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Guards against the 0 sentinel. Reads the children List at offset 24, iterates
its entries, recurses into each child. Then destroys the List itself and
finally deallocates the 32-byte node record. The value pointer is intentionally
not freed - it points into the source buffer owned by the lexer.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(n) over the number of nodes in the subtree. Recursion depth bounded by AST
depth, which for assembly is typically shallow (instruction -> operand).
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Must be called exactly once per tree root. Calling twice is a double-free of
the underlying List and node memory.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "destroy_arm_node" takes node as Integer:
    Note: Recursively free AST node and children

    If node is equal to 0:
        Return
    End If

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with node, 24
    Let child_count be proc size from List with children
    Let i be 0
    While i is less than child_count:
        Let child be proc get from List with children, i
        proc destroy_arm_node from child
        Set i to i plus 1
    End While
    proc destroy from List with children
    proc deallocate from Layout with node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Top-level entry point. Produces a synthetic ARM_INSTRUCTION root whose
children are the actual top-level statements (directives, labels,
instructions). Using ARM_INSTRUCTION as the root tag is intentional: it gives
the to_hir traversal a consistent type to dispatch on for the root.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Creates an empty root node, then loops the token stream. Newlines (token type
14) are silently skipped to handle blank lines and statement separators. Any
non-newline token kicks off parse_statement; non-null results are attached as
children of the root. Termination occurs on a 0 token pointer (EOF sentinel)
or token_type 0 (true EOF).
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(t) where t is the number of tokens. Each call to parse_statement consumes
at least one token, guaranteeing progress and finite termination.
@End Performance_Hints

@Security_Scope:
Operates on attacker-controlled tokens. Malformed input may produce a tree
with skipped statements (parse_statement returns 0 on unrecognised tokens),
never an infinite loop.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse entire ARM assembly source into AST

    Let root be proc create_arm_node with ARM_INSTRUCTION, 0, 0

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token from parser
        If token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Note: Skip newlines
        If token_type is equal to 14:
            proc advance_token from parser
            Note: Continue to next token
        Otherwise:
            Let statement be proc parse_statement from parser
            If statement is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with root, statement
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return root
End Process

@Reasoning:
Statement-level dispatch. ARM source has three statement forms at this level:
directives ('.text', '.global foo'), labels ('foo:'), and instructions
('add r0, r1, r2'). An identifier is ambiguous - it is a label only if the
following token is a colon - so we disambiguate via a one-token lookahead.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Inspects current token type. Token type 3 -> parse_directive. Token type 15
(identifier) -> is_label_definition decides between parse_label and
parse_identifier_operand. Token type 1 -> parse_instruction. Anything else is
malformed; skip_to_newline drops the line and returns 0.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted input. Unknown statements are dropped to a newline rather than
aborting, ensuring forward progress on malformed assembly.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_statement" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse a single ARM assembly statement

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Parse directive
    If token_type is equal to 3:
        Return proc parse_directive from parser
    End If

    Note: Parse label or identifier
    If token_type is equal to 15:
        Note: Check if this is a label (next token is colon)
        Let is_label be proc is_label_definition from parser
        If is_label is equal to 1:
            Return proc parse_label from parser
        Otherwise:
            Note: Treat as identifier operand
            Return proc parse_identifier_operand from parser
        End If
    End If

    Note: Parse instruction
    If token_type is equal to 1:
        Return proc parse_instruction from parser
    End If

    Note: Unknown statement type - skip to next line
    proc skip_to_newline from parser
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
A GAS directive is the leading directive token followed by comma-separated
operand expressions and terminated by a newline. The directive node retains
the lexeme (e.g. '.global') and operands attach as children, mirroring the
shape of instruction nodes so to_hir can use one operand-walker for both.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads value_ptr and value_length off the current token, builds an ARM_DIRECTIVE
node, advances past it. Then loops: stop on newline (advance and break), stop
on EOF (break). Each non-terminator token is parsed via parse_operand and
attached. A trailing comma is silently consumed between operands.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) where k is operand count.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_directive" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse assembler directive

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let directive be proc create_arm_node with ARM_DIRECTIVE, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token from parser

    Note: Parse directive arguments until newline
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc current_token from parser
        If current is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let current_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current, 0
        If current_type is equal to 14:  Note: Newline
            proc advance_token from parser
            Break
        End If

        If current_type is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse directive argument
        Let arg be proc parse_operand from parser
        If arg is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with directive, arg
        End If

        Note: Handle comma separator
        Let comma_check be proc current_token from parser
        If comma_check is not equal to 0:
            Let comma_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with comma_check, 0
            If comma_type is equal to 7:
                proc advance_token from parser
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return directive
End Process

@Reasoning:
Called only after is_label_definition has confirmed the identifier-colon
pattern, so this proc just packages the identifier lexeme as an ARM_LABEL
node and consumes both the identifier and the colon. Any trailing tokens on
the same line (e.g. label-on-same-line-as-instruction is rare but legal in
GAS) are skipped to keep one statement per line.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures value_ptr/length from the identifier token, builds the ARM_LABEL
node, advances. Reads the next token expecting type 13 (colon) and consumes
it if present (defensive). Calls skip_to_newline to drop any leftover tokens
on the same line.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_label" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse label definition

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let label be proc create_arm_node with ARM_LABEL, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token from parser

    Note: Consume colon
    Let colon_token be proc current_token from parser
    If colon_token is not equal to 0:
        Let colon_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with colon_token, 0
        If colon_type is equal to 13:
            proc advance_token from parser
        End If
    End If

    Note: Skip to newline
    proc skip_to_newline from parser

    Return label
End Process

@Reasoning:
An instruction is a mnemonic followed by zero or more operands separated by
commas and terminated by a newline. Mirrors parse_directive structurally
because both consume the same operand syntax; the only difference is the
node tag and the lexeme being a TOKEN_INSTRUCTION vs TOKEN_DIRECTIVE.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures the mnemonic lexeme into an ARM_INSTRUCTION node, advances. Loops:
stop on newline (advance and break), stop on EOF (break). Each operand is
parsed via parse_operand and attached. Inter-operand commas are silently
consumed.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) where k is operand count. ARM instructions typically have <= 4 operands.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_instruction" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse ARM instruction with operands

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let instruction be proc create_arm_node with ARM_INSTRUCTION, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token from parser

    Note: Parse operands until newline
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let current be proc current_token from parser
        If current is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let current_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with current, 0
        If current_type is equal to 14:  Note: Newline
            proc advance_token from parser
            Break
        End If

        If current_type is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse operand
        Let operand be proc parse_operand from parser
        If operand is not equal to 0:
            proc add_child with instruction, operand
        End If

        Note: Handle comma separator
        Let comma_check be proc current_token from parser
        If comma_check is not equal to 0:
            Let comma_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with comma_check, 0
            If comma_type is equal to 7:
                proc advance_token from parser
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return instruction
End Process

@Reasoning:
Operand-level dispatch table. ARM operands fall into a closed set of forms:
register (possibly with shift), '#'-prefixed immediate, '[...]' memory
reference, '{...}' register list, raw identifier (label ref), raw number
(directive context), and string (directive context). Routing here lets every
caller (instructions and directives alike) share one operand grammar.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the current token type and dispatches: 2 -> parse_register_or_shifted,
12 -> parse_immediate, 8 -> parse_memory, 10 -> parse_register_list,
15 -> parse_identifier_operand, 5 -> parse_number_operand, 6 -> parse_string_operand.
Unknown tokens are advanced past and 0 is returned.
@End Implementation

@Security_Scope:
Untrusted input; unknown tokens advance the cursor to guarantee progress.
@End Security_Scope

Process called "parse_operand" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse ARM instruction operand

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

    Note: Parse register
    If token_type is equal to 2:
        Return proc parse_register_or_shifted from parser
    End If

    Note: Parse immediate value (# prefix)
    If token_type is equal to 12:
        Return proc parse_immediate from parser
    End If

    Note: Parse memory reference [...]
    If token_type is equal to 8:
        Return proc parse_memory from parser
    End If

    Note: Parse register list {...}
    If token_type is equal to 10:
        Return proc parse_register_list from parser
    End If

    Note: Parse identifier (label reference)
    If token_type is equal to 15:
        Return proc parse_identifier_operand from parser
    End If

    Note: Parse number (direct number without #)
    If token_type is equal to 5:
        Return proc parse_number_operand from parser
    End If

    Note: Parse string
    If token_type is equal to 6:
        Return proc parse_string_operand from parser
    End If

    Note: Unknown operand - skip
    proc advance_token from parser
    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM register operands can be wrapped in a shift expression like 'r1, LSL #2'.
We always parse the base register first, then peek for a TOKEN_SHIFT to
decide whether to wrap it in an ARM_SHIFTED node. This avoids backtracking
in parse_operand.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Calls parse_register to get the base, then inspects the next token. If its
type is 17 (TOKEN_SHIFT), allocates an ARM_SHIFTED node, attaches the
register as first child, then attaches an ARM_IDENTIFIER node holding the
shift mnemonic lexeme, then parses the shift amount via parse_operand
(typically #imm or register) and attaches it. Returns the shifted wrapper.
If no shift follows, returns the bare register.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_register_or_shifted" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse register, possibly with shift operation

    Let register be proc parse_register from parser

    Note: Check if next token is a shift operator
    Let shift_token be proc current_token from parser
    If shift_token is not equal to 0:
        Let shift_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with shift_token, 0
        If shift_type is equal to 17:  Note: Shift operator
            Note: Create shifted operand node
            Let shifted be proc create_arm_node with ARM_SHIFTED, 0, 0
            proc add_child with shifted, register

            Note: Add shift operator
            Let shift_value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with shift_token, 8
            Let shift_value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with shift_token, 16
            Let shift_op be proc create_arm_node with ARM_IDENTIFIER, shift_value_ptr, shift_value_length
            proc add_child with shifted, shift_op
            proc advance_token from parser

            Note: Parse shift amount (# prefix or register)
            Let shift_amount be proc parse_operand from parser
            If shift_amount is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with shifted, shift_amount
            End If

            Return shifted
        End If
    End If

    Return register
End Process

@Reasoning:
The lexer already classified registers via classify_token, so the parser
trusts TOKEN_REGISTER and just wraps the lexeme in an ARM_REGISTER node
without re-validating. Validation of bank membership belongs in semantic
analysis.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads value_ptr/length off the current TOKEN_REGISTER token, allocates an
ARM_REGISTER node carrying the lexeme, advances the cursor.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_register" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse register (r0-r15, sp, lr, pc, etc.)

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let register be proc create_arm_node with ARM_REGISTER, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token from parser

    Return register
End Process

@Reasoning:
ARM immediates appear as '#<value>'. The '#' is purely a syntactic marker;
the numeric value lives in the token following it. We discard the '#' and
keep the numeric lexeme in an ARM_IMMEDIATE node.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Advances past the '#' TOKEN_HASH unconditionally, reads value_ptr/length off
the next token (number or identifier - identifier covers labels used as
immediates), wraps it in an ARM_IMMEDIATE node, advances. Returns 0 if the
'#' is at EOF.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_immediate" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse immediate value (#123)

    proc advance_token from parser  Note: Skip #

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    If token is equal to 0:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let immediate be proc create_arm_node with ARM_IMMEDIATE, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token from parser

    Return immediate
End Process

@Reasoning:
Memory references use the ARM '[base, offset]' form, optionally with a '!'
writeback marker. We capture the base register, optional offset (immediate
or register), and writeback indicator into a single ARM_MEMORY node whose
children encode all three. We do not parse pre/post-indexed variants beyond
this; the to_hir layer infers indexing mode from the children.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes '['. Allocates ARM_MEMORY. If the next token is a register, parses
it via parse_register and attaches as first child. If a comma follows,
consumes it and parses the offset via parse_operand (handles #imm, register,
or shifted register) and attaches it. Consumes the expected ']'. If the next
token is '!' (TOKEN_EXCLAIM, type 16), attaches a synthetic ARM_IDENTIFIER
sentinel as a third child to encode writeback and consumes the '!'.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) modulo the optional inner operand parse.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_memory" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse memory reference [base, offset]

    proc advance_token from parser  Note: Skip [

    Let memory be proc create_arm_node with ARM_MEMORY, 0, 0

    Note: Parse base register
    Let base_token be proc current_token from parser
    If base_token is not equal to 0:
        Let base_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with base_token, 0
        If base_type is equal to 2:
            Let base be proc parse_register from parser
            proc add_child with memory, base
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for comma (offset follows)
    Let comma_token be proc current_token from parser
    If comma_token is not equal to 0:
        Let comma_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with comma_token, 0
        If comma_type is equal to 7:
            proc advance_token from parser

            Note: Parse offset (immediate or register)
            Let offset be proc parse_operand from parser
            If offset is not equal to 0:
                proc add_child with memory, offset
            End If
        End If
    End If

    Note: Expect ]
    Let rbracket be proc current_token from parser
    If rbracket is not equal to 0:
        Let rbracket_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with rbracket, 0
        If rbracket_type is equal to 9:
            proc advance_token from parser
        End If
    End If

    Note: Check for writeback indicator (!)
    Let exclaim_token be proc current_token from parser
    If exclaim_token is not equal to 0:
        Let exclaim_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with exclaim_token, 0
        If exclaim_type is equal to 16:
            Note: Mark as writeback by adding exclaim node
            Let writeback be proc create_arm_node with ARM_IDENTIFIER, 0, 0
            proc add_child with memory, writeback
            proc advance_token from parser
        End If
    End If

    Return memory
End Process

@Reasoning:
LDM/STM and PUSH/POP take a brace-enclosed register list. We flatten the list
into an ARM_REGISTER_LIST whose children are ARM_REGISTER nodes. Range
notation ('r0-r3') is treated as separate registers at this layer; expanding
ranges is a semantic-analysis concern, not a parsing one.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Consumes '{'. Allocates ARM_REGISTER_LIST. Loops: stop on '}' (type 11,
advance and break); if the token is a register (type 2), parse it via
parse_register and attach. After each register, consume an optional comma.
EOF terminates the loop. Returns the list node.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(k) where k is the number of registers in the list (typically <= 16).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "parse_register_list" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse register list {r0-r3, lr}

    proc advance_token from parser  Note: Skip {

    Let register_list be proc create_arm_node with ARM_REGISTER_LIST, 0, 0

    Note: Parse registers until }
    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token from parser
        If token is equal to 0:
            Break
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0

        Note: Check for closing brace
        If token_type is equal to 11:
            proc advance_token from parser
            Break
        End If

        Note: Parse register
        If token_type is equal to 2:
            Let register be proc parse_register from parser
            proc add_child with register_list, register
        End If

        Note: Handle comma separator
        Let comma_check be proc current_token from parser
        If comma_check is not equal to 0:
            Let comma_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with comma_check, 0
            If comma_type is equal to 7:
                proc advance_token from parser
            End If
        End If
    End While

    Return register_list
End Process

@Reasoning:
When an identifier appears in operand position it is a symbol or label
reference, not a label definition (parse_statement already disambiguated).
We wrap the lexeme in an ARM_IDENTIFIER node; resolution to a symbol address
happens later.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures value_ptr/length, builds an ARM_IDENTIFIER node, advances.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_identifier_operand" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse identifier (label reference or symbol)

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let identifier be proc create_arm_node with ARM_IDENTIFIER, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token from parser

    Return identifier
End Process

@Reasoning:
Some directive operands accept a bare number with no '#' prefix (e.g.
'.word 42'). We still tag the result with ARM_IMMEDIATE because semantically
a directive's numeric operand is an immediate value; this lets to_hir share
one numeric-conversion path.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures value_ptr/length from the TOKEN_NUMBER token, wraps in an
ARM_IMMEDIATE node, advances.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_number_operand" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse number operand

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let number be proc create_arm_node with ARM_IMMEDIATE, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token from parser

    Return number
End Process

@Reasoning:
String literals appear only as directive operands (.ascii "...", .asciz "..."
etc.). We currently tag them as ARM_IDENTIFIER because the lexeme - including
the surrounding quotes - is preserved verbatim and the HIR lowerer recognises
the leading quote.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Captures value_ptr/length from the TOKEN_STRING token, wraps in an
ARM_IDENTIFIER node, advances.
@End Implementation

Process called "parse_string_operand" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Parse string operand

    Let token be proc current_token from parser
    Let value_ptr be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 8
    Let value_length be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 16

    Let string_node be proc create_arm_node with ARM_IDENTIFIER, value_ptr, value_length
    proc advance_token from parser

    Return string_node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Disambiguates an identifier at statement position. Without lookahead we
cannot tell whether 'foo' is a label or an operand-style reference, but if
the next token is ':' it must be a label definition. One token of lookahead
is sufficient; we never need to commit and roll back.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the parser's token list and current index. If current+1 is past the
end, returns 0. Otherwise reads token at current+1 and returns 1 if its type
is 13 (TOKEN_COLON), else 0. The parser cursor is not modified.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "is_label_definition" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Check if current position is a label definition (identifier followed by colon)

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let current_index be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    If current_index plus 1 is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Let next_token be proc get from List with tokens, current_index plus 1
    Let next_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with next_token, 0

    If next_type is equal to 13:  Note: Colon
        Return 1
    End If

    Return 0
End Process

@Reasoning:
Read-only accessor used by every parse_* helper before deciding what to do.
Returning 0 instead of asserting on out-of-range index turns end-of-stream
into a regular control-flow signal that every caller already checks.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the tokens list and current index off the parser. If current is at or
past List.size, returns 0; otherwise returns List.get at current.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(1) accessor. Called many times per token.
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "current_token" takes parser as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Get current token without advancing

    Let tokens be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 8
    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    Let token_count be proc size from List with tokens

    If current is greater than or equal to token_count:
        Return 0
    End If

    Return proc get from List with tokens, current
End Process

@Reasoning:
Cursor mutation isolated to one helper so every parse_* path advances
consistently. Does not bounds-check because current_token's out-of-range
test handles end-of-stream uniformly.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads current at offset 16, writes current+1 back to offset 16.
@End Implementation

Process called "advance_token" takes parser as Integer:
    Note: Move to next token

    Let current be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parser, 16
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with parser, 16, current plus 1
End Process

@Reasoning:
Recovery primitive used when a statement is unrecognised. ARM source is
line-structured so dropping the rest of the line is a deterministic, sane
recovery point that lets parse continue with the next statement.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Loops reading current_token. On 0 (out of range) or token_type 0 (EOF),
returns without advancing. On token_type 14 (newline), advances past it and
returns. Otherwise advances and continues. Worst case consumes the rest of
the token list.
@End Implementation

@Performance_Hints:
O(remaining tokens on line).
@End Performance_Hints

Process called "skip_to_newline" takes parser as Integer:
    Note: Skip tokens until newline or EOF

    While 1 is equal to 1:
        Let token be proc current_token from parser
        If token is equal to 0:
            Return
        End If

        Let token_type be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with token, 0
        If token_type is equal to 14:  Note: Newline
            proc advance_token from parser
            Return
        End If

        If token_type is equal to 0:  Note: EOF
            Return
        End If

        proc advance_token from parser
    End While
End Process

@Reasoning:
Single point of allocation for ArmNode to keep the 32-byte layout in one
place. Every node gets its own children list at construction even if it
turns out to be a leaf - we trade a small allocation for simpler walker code
(no null-children check needed).
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Allocates 32 bytes via Layout.allocate, writes node_type/value/value_length
at offsets 0/8/16, creates a fresh List and stores its handle at offset 24.
Returns the node pointer.
@End Implementation

Process called "create_arm_node" takes node_type as Integer, value as Integer, value_length as Integer returns Integer:
    Note: Create new AST node

    Let node be proc allocate from Layout with 32
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 0, node_type
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 8, value
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 16, value_length
    Let children be proc create from List
    proc memory_set_int64 from Layout with node, 24, children
    Return node
End Process

@Reasoning:
Helper isolates the children-list mutation so future changes to the ArmNode
layout (e.g. moving children to a different offset or switching list type)
only require touching this one proc.
@End Reasoning

@Implementation:
Reads the children List handle at parent offset 24 and pushes child onto it.
Ownership of child transfers to parent.
@End Implementation

Process called "add_child" takes parent as Integer, child as Integer:
    Note: Add child node to parent

    Let children be proc memory_get_int64 from Layout with parent, 24
    proc push from List with children, child
End Process
